solution:
Make a diagram. Two geometric figures intersect if they have one or more points in common. Draw two circles which intersect in $2$ points. Draw a line which intersects the two circles in $4$ points. Draw another line which intersects the two circles in $4$ points and also intersects the first line. There are $\boxed{11}$ points of intersection. [asy]

draw(Circle((-0.7,0),1));
draw(Circle((0.7,0),1));

dot((0,0));

dot((0,0.7));
dot((0,-0.7));

draw((0,0)--(-2,0.6),Arrow);
draw((0,0)--(-2,-0.6),Arrow);
draw((0,0)--(2,0.6),Arrow);
draw((0,0)--(2,-0.6),Arrow);

dot((-1.58,0.47));
dot((-1.58,-0.47));
dot((1.58,0.47));
dot((1.58,-0.47));

dot((-0.29,0.08));
dot((-0.29,-0.08));
dot((0.29,0.08));
dot((0.29,-0.08));

[/asy]

Notice how the parentheses are only around pairs of numbers that are being multiplied or divided. Since multiplication and division are performed before addition and subtraction, it doesn't matter if we remove the parentheses. That's why  \begin{align*}
&54+(98\div14)+(23\cdot 17)-200-(312\div 6)\\
&=54+98\div14+23\cdot17-200-312\div 6\\
&=\boxed{200}.\end{align*}

