problem:
For some constants $a$ and $b,$ let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
ax + b & \text{if } x < 2, \\
8 - 3x & \text{if } x \ge 2.
\end{array}
\right.\]The function $f$ has the property that $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x.$ What is $a + b?$

solution:
The distance between the midpoint of $\overline{AB}$ and an endpoint of $\overline{AB}$ is equal to half of the length of $\overline{AB}$. By the distance formula,

\begin{align*}
AB &= \sqrt{((t-4)-(-2))^2 + ((-1)-(t+3))^2}\\
&= \sqrt{(t-2)^2+(t+4)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{2t^2 + 4t + 20}
\end{align*}Also, we know that $(AB/2)^2 = t^2/2 \Longrightarrow AB = 2\sqrt{t^2/2} = \sqrt{2t^2}$. Setting these two expressions equal and squaring, we obtain $$AB^2 = 2t^2 = 2t^2 + 4t + 20 \Longrightarrow 4t + 20 = 0.$$Thus, $t = \boxed{-5}$.

Since $a$ varies inversely with $b^2$, $(a)(b^2)=k$ for some constant $k$. If $a=9$ when $b=2$, then $k=(9)(2^2)=(9)(4)=36$. So if $b=3$, \begin{align*} (a)(3^2)&=36
\\ 9a&=36
\\\Rightarrow\qquad a&=\boxed{4}
\end{align*}

